## Implementation

The datasets presented in this study were generated using the **Data_aggregation** pipeline, a modular framework originally developed for extracting and analyzing Open Educational Resources (OER) from the Saxon OPAL learning management system. The pipeline has since been extended to support multiple content sources, including local PDF documents and LiaScript courses from GitHub repositories. For this study, the pipeline implements the three-phase methodology described above (repository discovery, indicator-based pre-selection, and AI-based validation) and handles metadata extraction, Git history analysis, and AI-powered content classification.

The pipeline is fully configurable through YAML configuration files, allowing researchers to customize data sources, processing stages, validation criteria, and output formats without modifying the source code. The complete configuration used for this study, including all search parameters, indicator definitions, AI validation prompts, and metadata extraction settings, is documented in the [`full.yaml`](https://github.com/TUBAF-IFI-ConnectedLecturer/Data_aggregation/blob/main/cl-pipeline/run/pipelines/liascript/config/full.yaml) configuration file.

The data collection and analysis for this study was conducted in December 2025. The entire process, including data aggregation, preprocessing, and AI-based analysis, required approximately 4 days of processing time. Reproducibility of the study is ensured through the publicly available repository, comprehensive installation instructions, and detailed configuration guidelines.

The complete pipeline source code, including all stage implementations, configuration files, and documentation, is publicly available at [Github](https://github.com/TUBAF-IFI-ConnectedLecturer/Data_aggregation).

## Ethical Considerations

All analyzed repositories are publicly accessible on GitHub, ensuring transparency and reproducibility of our research. While repository owners and contributors remain identifiable through their public repositories, we do not individually name them without explicit consent. Our analysis focuses exclusively on repository metadata and does not include user profiles or private information. Furthermore, we strictly respect repository licenses in all aspects of data usage and reporting.
